This part of the code encodes the text into a bytes object using the ASCII encoding while ignoring characters that cannot be represented in ASCII. The ASCII encoding is a character encoding standard that represents text using a 7-bit binary code, which means it can represent only a limited set of characters, primarily in the English language.

If a character in the text cannot be represented in ASCII, it will be replaced or "ignored." In other words, non-ASCII characters will be removed from the text during this encoding step. .decode(): After encoding the text using ASCII and removing non-ASCII characters, the .decode() method is called to convert the encoded bytes object back into a string. This step is necessary because the result of encoding is a bytes object, and you typically want to work with text as strings.

In [ ]:
opinions = productivity['review']

opinions =list(opinions)
categories = list(categories)

assert(len(stars) == len(opinions) == len(categories))
In [ ]:
from tqdm import tqdm

stats_data = []

# Use tqdm to track the progress
for i, (star, opinion, cat) in tqdm(enumerate(zip(stars, opinions, categories)), total=len(stars)):
    # Process the review content (opinion) using spaCy
    sample = u.spacy_sentences(nlp, opinion)
    for sent in sample:
        nm = u.search_adjectives(sent)
        u.verb_adjectives(sent, adjective_map=nm)
        for n, adjs in nm.items():
            for a in adjs:
                # Append data to stats_data
                stats_data.append({
                    'doc': i,
                    'category': cat,
                    'adj': a.lemma_.lower(),
                    'noun': n.lemma_.lower(),
                    'star': star  # Include the star rating
                })

# Create a DataFrame
S = pd.DataFrame(stats_data)

In [ ]:
min_freq = 10

adj_noun = Sdoc.groupby(['adj', 'noun']).count()
adj_noun = adj_noun[adj_noun.doc > min_freq]

adj = Sdoc.groupby('adj').count()['doc']
adj = pd.DataFrame(adj[adj > min_freq])

noun = Sdoc.groupby('noun').count()['doc']
noun = pd.DataFrame(noun[noun > min_freq])
In [ ]:
adj_noun_sum = adj_noun.sum()['doc']
adj_noun['p'] = adj_noun.doc / adj_noun_sum
adj_sum = adj.sum()['doc']
adj['p'] = adj.doc / adj_sum
noun_sum = noun.sum()['doc']
noun['p'] = noun.doc / noun_sum

cat_noun = Scat[Scat.doc > min_freq].copy()

cat_p = pd.DataFrame(cat_noun.groupby('category')['doc'].sum())
cat_p = cat_p[cat_p.doc > min_freq]

noun_p = pd.DataFrame(cat_noun.groupby('noun')['doc'].sum())

noun_p = noun_p[noun_p.doc > min_freq]
cat_noun_sum = cat_noun.doc.sum()

cat_noun['p'] = cat_noun.doc / cat_noun_sum
cat_p['p'] = cat_p.doc / cat_p.doc.sum()
noun_p['p'] = noun_p.doc / noun_p.doc.sum()

pmi = []

                'noun': row['noun'],

In [ ]:
X = np.zeros((Sn.shape[0], len(features)))
categories, adjs, nouns = Sn.category.values, Sn.adj.values, Sn.noun.values
for i, c in enumerate(categories):
    a = adjs[i]
    n = nouns[i]
    X[i, features.index((c, n))] = scaled[i,0]
    X[i, features.index((a, n))] = scaled[i,1]
